1775835586135076	bones-dev	itc:v3:AWKSZJkkk5JkmZMxAAAAQatWqrq1bWwAAAE3jww		item.create	bn-3mqr	{"description":"Follow-up from bn-17xg. The mimalloc A/B confirmed that the TUI RSS problem is NOT an allocator issue — system allocator keeps RSS at ~6 MB for a 750-item workload and mimalloc is actually worse (more preallocated arenas).\n\nThe most likely real cause is the ORT semantic-search stack in bones-search with the semantic-ort feature. It loads ONNX models and tokenizer state that stay resident across every TUI tick.\n\nPlan:\n1. MEASURE first: use the existing dhat-heap feature (cargo bench --bench tui_memory --features dhat-heap, or cargo run --features dhat-heap). Point dh_view.html at the resulting dhat-heap.json and identify the top retained-size consumers.\n2. Expand the tui_memory bench with a scenario that triggers semantic search (currently it only exercises list/detail/render — no search). Needed to reproduce the 1.6 GB figure.\n3. If ORT is the culprit: evaluate (a) lazy load on first search only, (b) drop model state on TUI idle, (c) switch to semantic-model2vec (lighter, already a feature), (d) disable semantic by default in the TUI.\n4. If it's not ORT: re-run dhat against the long-running TUI and report top 3 consumers with recommendations.\n\nExit: either a concrete fix with before/after RSS measurements, or a written rejection with data explaining what the real constraint is.\n\nSupersedes the original framing of the TUI RSS work. Reference benches/ALLOCATORS.md for the elimination of allocator as a cause.","kind":"task","labels":["perf","memory"],"parent":"bn-1582","size":"m","title":"Investigate 1.6GB TUI RSS: profile semantic search model state"}	blake3:KZhjQL41BjTI9AgNe9nK-a-rBieqqitSrIAzH2_jEKs
